PROMPT data_storage_architectures
WITH BUDGET 8000 tokens
USING MODEL "claude-sonnet-4-5"

SELECT
    system_role("You are a data architecture expert specializing in modern data storage systems, data engineering, and the evolution of enterprise data platforms with deep knowledge of data lakes, data warehouses, and lakehouse architectures.")

GENERATE
    compare_data_architectures("Explain the fundamental differences between data lakes and data warehouses, and introduce the concept of data lakehouses, covering: data warehouse definition as a structured, centralized repository that stores processed, clean data in predefined schemas optimized for analytical queries and business intelligence, typically using star or snowflake schemas with ETL processes that extract, transform, and load data before storage, versus data lake definition as a centralized repository that stores raw, unprocessed data in its native format including structured, semi-structured, and unstructured data like JSON, XML, images, videos, and log files using schema-on-read approach, key architectural differences including data warehouses' structured approach with predefined schemas, data modeling, and optimized for known analytical use cases, while data lakes use flexible storage that accepts any data format without upfront schema definition, processing paradigms where data warehouses follow ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) with data transformed before storage ensuring quality and consistency, versus data lakes using ELT (Extract, Load, Transform) where raw data is stored first and transformed during analysis, cost considerations showing data warehouses as expensive due to specialized hardware, software licensing, and storage optimization, while data lakes leverage low-cost storage like cloud object stores (S3, Azure Blob) making them more cost-effective for large volumes, performance characteristics where data warehouses provide fast, predictable query performance for structured analytical workloads due to pre-processing and indexing, while data lakes may have slower query times but offer flexibility for diverse analytical needs, data quality and governance differences with data warehouses maintaining high data quality through ETL validation and cleansing processes, versus data lakes storing raw data that may contain quality issues requiring downstream validation, use cases where data warehouses excel for traditional BI reporting, regulatory compliance, and well-defined analytical workflows, while data lakes support data science, machine learning, real-time analytics, and exploratory data analysis, the evolution to data lakehouse architecture that combines the flexibility and cost-effectiveness of data lakes with the performance and reliability of data warehouses, key lakehouse features including ACID transactions, schema enforcement and evolution, unified batch and streaming data processing, direct access to data in open formats like Delta Lake or Apache Iceberg, how lakehouses address traditional data lake challenges including data swamps, lack of ACID properties, poor performance for BI queries, and data quality issues, benefits of lakehouse approach including reduced data duplication, simplified architecture by eliminating separate data lake and warehouse systems, support for diverse workloads from BI to ML on a single platform, practical implementation examples using technologies like Databricks Delta Lake, Apache Hudi, or Apache Iceberg that provide lakehouse capabilities, and decision framework for choosing between traditional data warehouse, data lake, or lakehouse architecture based on organizational needs, data types, analytical requirements, and budget constraints.")
WITH OUTPUT BUDGET 4000 tokens, TEMPERATURE 0.2, FORMAT markdown;